faqs:
  - q: "What is the best food for a doodle crossbreed?"
    a: "There isn't one 'doodle food', because a doodle isn't one dog — a Cavapoo can be a 5kg lapdog and a Labradoodle a 30kg athlete, and either can inherit the Poodle's easy coat or a Spaniel's itchy skin. The reliable approach is to feed for what's actually in front of you: choose a complete food matched to your dog's adult size and life stage, favour a named single protein and omega-3 for the near-universal doodle curly coat, and keep the recipe simple so that if a sensitivity shows up you can spot the trigger. Start there, watch how your dog does over a few weeks, and only specialise once its real needs are clear. Our sensitive-stomach pillar and grain-free roundup are the two most useful starting points."
  - q: "Do Cavapoos, Cockapoos and Labradoodles need different food?"
    a: "By size and energy, yes; by breed 'type', not really. All three share the same core doodle brief — an unpredictable mix, a curly Poodle-influenced coat that thrives on omega-3, and a Spaniel or Retriever parent that can pass on food-linked ear or skin sensitivity. What differs is scale: a Cavapoo (typically 5–9kg) needs a small-breed calorie-dense food and a small kibble for a little mouth; a Cockapoo (6–11kg) sits just above it; a Labradoodle (often 20–30kg+) needs large-breed lean-growth feeding as a puppy to protect its joints. Feed to the adult weight your dog is heading for, not to the word 'doodle' on the pedigree."
  - q: "Why can't I just pick food for the specific doodle type?"
    a: "Because a crossbreed doesn't reliably inherit a predictable blend of its parents. Two Cockapoo littermates can turn out completely different — one with the Poodle's low-shedding easy coat and cast-iron gut, the other with the Cocker's feathered ears and chicken sensitivity. Breed-average advice assumes an 'average' dog that your individual doodle may not be. That's why the doodle rule is start simple and watch: begin with a clean, single-protein, size-appropriate food, then adjust based on the actual dog — its coat, its stools, its ears, its waistline — rather than a breed stereotype."
  - q: "Do doodles have sensitive stomachs or skin?"
    a: "Some do, some don't — and that's exactly the point. The Poodle side is generally robust, but Cavalier, Cocker and (to a lesser extent) Labrador/Golden parents can pass on a tendency toward food-responsive itching, recurrent ear infections and loose stools. Because you can't predict which way your doodle went until it grows up, feeding a simple, limited-ingredient recipe from the start makes any sensitivity easier to catch and manage. If your doodle is itchy, ear-prone or has soft stools, work through our sensitive-stomach pillar and rule out fleas and environmental allergies first — only around 10–15% of itching is food-related."
  - q: "How should I feed a doodle's curly coat?"
    a: "The curly, low-shedding coat is the one trait nearly every doodle inherits from its Poodle parent, and it's high-maintenance from the inside as well as the groomer's table. Omega-3 fatty acids (EPA and DHA, richest in oily fish and fish oil) support the skin barrier and coat condition, so a recipe that names fish or added fish oil helps keep the coat glossy and less prone to matting and dryness. Named single proteins and a complete, balanced food do the rest — no supplement replaces good grooming, but good nutrition makes the coat easier to keep."
  - q: "How much should I feed my doodle?"
    a: "Feed to calories and body condition, not to a cup measurement or the word 'doodle'. Because doodles span from 5kg to 30kg-plus, the daily amount varies enormously — a Cavapoo might eat 100–150g of kibble a day while a standard Labradoodle eats three or four times that. Work out your dog's actual need from its adult (or, for a puppy, current) weight and life stage using our dog food calculator, then adjust up or down until you can feel its ribs easily but not see them. Re-check whenever the coat gets a full clip, because a freshly groomed doodle can hide — or reveal — weight the fluff was masking."
  - q: "Are doodle puppies fed differently by size?"
    a: "Yes — and this is where the size spread matters most. A small doodle puppy (Cavapoo, Toy Cockapoo) needs a calorie-dense small-breed puppy food fed little-and-often, because tiny pups have small fuel reserves. A large doodle puppy (standard Labradoodle, Goldendoodle) needs the opposite discipline: lean, controlled growth on a large-breed puppy food, because overfeeding a fast-growing big-breed pup drives joint and hip problems. Match the puppy food to the adult size your doodle is heading for, and see our how-much-to-feed-a-puppy guide for the growth-curve maths."
  - q: "Is grain-free food better for doodles?"
    a: "Not automatically. Grain-free can help the minority of doodles with a genuine grain sensitivity, but most do perfectly well on a good-quality food that includes wholegrains. What matters more is a named meat as the first ingredient, a simple recipe you can troubleshoot, and omega-3 for the coat. If you do choose grain-free, pick a recipe built on named meat and vegetables rather than one leaning heavily on peas, lentils and chickpeas — our is-grain-free-good guide explains why."
